+# EXPERIENCE AUDIT — CODEX — 2026-07-19
+
+**Evidence used:** code only (`src/**`) plus `docs/polish/baseline-sweep/manifest.json` for route inventory. No screenshots or live-app inspection were used, and no other audit/delight report was read. Counts below cover production `.ts`, `.tsx`, and `.css` under `src`, excluding tests, unless stated otherwise.
+
+## Verdict: why it reads 4/10
+
+The product reads as 4/10 because its intelligence is stronger than its presentation contract. The plan engine, check-in lifecycle, signature safeguards, PDFs, and granular queries encode serious capability, but the interface presents that capability as long stacks of neutral cards, tables, raw controls, and state-specific text rather than a coherent Roberto-led service. The root causes, in order, are: (1) the core coach loop is not choreographed—seven intake pages lead into a seven-section generation form and then a six-tab, 1,920-line review surface, while the generation “magic moment” is only a disabled button label; (2) identity fragments among teal app tokens, legacy navy/zinc inline styles, and a separate navy/gold PDF system; (3) state handling is locally competent but systemically inconsistent, especially on portal pages where query failures can look like empty data; (4) mobile and accessibility basics are partly present but not enforced by shared primitives; and (5) progress is reported as data, not interpreted as a motivating clinical story. The result feels like a capable internal admin tool attached to a serviceable patient portal, not one premium end-to-end nutrition experience.
+
+## Macro journey scores
+
+| Journey | Score /10 | Top blocker | Fix |
+|---|---:|---|---|
+| 1. COACH: first-run/empty dashboard → onboarding | 3 | The welcome CTA links to `/clients/new`, while the route inventory exposes intake at `/plans/new` (`src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:523`; `src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:542`; `docs/polish/baseline-sweep/manifest.json:119`). | Replace the dead CTA, then make first run a three-step checklist—create client, capture baseline, generate first plan—with completion state and resume points. |
+| 2. COACH: morning triage | 5 | Useful counts and flags exist, but they are split across KPI cards, alerts, monitoring, training, and notifications; the monitoring summary’s second query has no loading/error treatment (`src/app/(dashboard)/monitoring/page.tsx:167`; `src/app/(dashboard)/monitoring/page.tsx:185`). | Build one ranked “Oggi” queue with reason, severity, last contact, and one-click resolution; preserve specialist tables as drill-down. |
+| 3. COACH: intake → generation → review → share | 3 | The path is three separate mental models: a seven-page intake (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:715`), seven stacked generator sections (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:572`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:982`), and six review tabs (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:787`); generation itself only says “Generazione in corso...” (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:1066`). | Rebuild as one persisted plan workspace: readiness check → required decisions → optional tuning → staged generation wait → exception-led review → approve/share ceremony. |
+| 4. COACH: client detail deep-dive | 5 | The page has substantial history, plans, check-ins, composition and actions, but independent fetch branches and long vertical density make the coach reassemble the clinical story (`src/app/(dashboard)/clients/[id]/page.tsx:620`; `src/app/(dashboard)/clients/[id]/page.tsx:776`; `src/app/(dashboard)/clients/[id]/page.tsx:2042`). | Lead with a longitudinal brief (“changed / why / action”), then group raw evidence into stable tabs with shared loading/error treatment and sticky client context. |
+| 5. COACH: invoice cycle | 5 | List states and PDF structure are solid, but the experience is status mechanics rather than a guided cycle; action success/errors remain local and the invoice artifact uses another visual system (`src/app/(dashboard)/invoices/page.tsx:283`; `src/app/(dashboard)/invoices/[id]/page.tsx:624`; `src/pdf/invoice-renderer.ts:175`). | Add a lifecycle rail (bozza → inviata → vista → pagata), confirmation receipts, overdue next actions, and the same brand/artifact tokens as plan and portal. |
+| 6. CLIENT: magic-link login → first impression | 6 | The login has a warm branded sent state, but the portal then mixes teal tokens with navy/gray inline cards and the client is called both “coach” and “nutrizionista” (`src/app/portal/login/page.tsx:60`; `src/app/portal/login/page.tsx:74`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:113`). | Carry one warm visual/copy system through the authenticated shell and make the first screen a personal “today” briefing from Roberto. |
+| 7. CLIENT: weekly check-in | 6 | Token validation, invalid-link, submit error, pending and success exist, but the form uses ten 36×36 controls and ends with a generic thank-you (`src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:229`; `src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:253`; `src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:101`). | Use ≥44px segmented controls, progressive question groups, saved progress, and a result receipt that explains what Roberto will review and when. |
+| 8. CLIENT: plan consumption | 5 | Meals and grams are present and Italian, but every day type expands into repeated meal cards with macro noise and no “today” default or quick substitution layer (`src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:238`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:259`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:278`). | Default to today’s plan; reveal alternates/macros on demand; add meal-time anchors, a compact shopping/prep view, and printable/offline continuity. |
+| 9. CLIENT: progress arc | 4 | The portal renders current measurements and separate per-metric lines, but there are no targets, clinical bands, milestones, or interpretation (`src/components/portal/measurements-view.tsx:80`; `src/components/portal/measurements-view.tsx:97`; `src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:12`). | Build a narrated progress arc: baseline → current → target, trend confidence, coach interpretation, honest milestones, and links to the behavior/check-in that produced change. |
+| 10. CLIENT: firma ceremony | 7 | This is the strongest journey: explicit consent, document availability gating, focus transfer, signed receipt, and download are encoded; visually it still resolves as a card/form rather than a trust ceremony (`src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:201`; `src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:234`; `src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:361`). | Preserve the legal rigor but add a short pre-sign summary, Roberto’s identity/credentials, a deliberate confirmation transition, and a durable “your signed copy” destination. |
+
+## Micro findings (ordered by leverage)
+
+### [P-COACH|M2/M4/M10|src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:572] The product’s magic is encoded as a configuration stack
+
+**Evidence:** After client selection, the page conditionally reveals Obiettivo & deficit, Struttura del piano, Macro overrides, Source swap, Configurazione Pasti, and Impostazioni Avanzate—seven card-like sections including selection (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:572`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:616`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:820`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:835`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:865`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:880`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:982`). Optional controls are not collapsed. The live week preview query is driven directly by schedule, session, deficit, macro, and source-pin inputs with no debounce (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:374`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:378`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:396`); while fetching, the only feedback is “· aggiornamento…” and the old values remain in place (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:1326`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:1357`).
+
+**Deduction:** The screen mirrors engine inputs instead of the coach’s decision sequence. Required, inferred, and exceptional decisions have equal visual weight; expert confidence drops because it is unclear what must be reviewed versus what is safely automatic. Direct refetches also make rapid edits feel unsettled and can show stale-looking numbers without a clear pending treatment.
+
+**Fix:** Turn the page into four progressive stages: (1) readiness and inherited client facts, (2) goal/safety decision, (3) week structure, (4) optional tuning. Put engine-owned defaults in a collapsed “Calcolato automaticamente” summary and reveal overrides only on intent. Debounce preview input by 300ms, preserve the last result with a visible updating veil, and label exactly which decision changed the output.
+
+### [P-COACH|M4|src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:430] Generation has no wait experience and no reveal
+
+**Evidence:** `plan.generate` routes immediately to review on success and stores only a raw error on failure (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:430`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:432`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:435`). During the mutation, the sole UI change is a disabled full-width button reading “Generazione in corso...” (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:1048`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:1066`). Across production source there is no Framer Motion/motion import; motion is mostly short hover/toggle transitions, while global CSS only guarantees reduced-motion suppression (`src/app/globals.css:143`; `src/components/ui/button.tsx:8`).
+
+**Deduction:** The highest-value computation feels like a blocking form submission. There is no evidence of work, no expectation setting, no reassurance that safety/periodisation logic is running, and no authored transition from inputs to a valuable artifact. This erases the product’s strongest possible signature moment.
+
+**Fix:** Replace the button-only pending state with a route-safe generation panel that names real phases (validating safety floor, calculating training-day expenditure, balancing macros, composing meals, checking constraints), communicates that the coach can stay or leave, handles long-tail delay/retry, and culminates in an accessible plan reveal. Use deterministic phase copy rather than fake percentages; respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.
+
+### [P-COACH|M2/M3|src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:64] Review is comprehensive but not exception-led
+
+**Evidence:** The 1,920-line review page exposes six peer tabs—Panoramica, Macro & Linee Guida, Pasti, Integratori, Monitoraggio, Versioni—through a flat horizontal strip (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:64`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:787`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:820`). Overview begins with a daily totals table, three summary stats, and conditional assumptions (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:873`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:876`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:919`). Approval has pending and success UI, but its mutation has no `onError`, and `handleApprove` only resets pending in `finally` (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:213`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:349`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:620`).
+
+**Deduction:** “Review” means manually touring the entire plan rather than resolving exceptions. Tabs reduce simultaneous density, but they do not establish completeness, risk, or a recommended scan order. A failed approval can reject without an authored recovery message at the exact trust point.
+
+**Fix:** Add a review rail with completion and issue counts: Safety, Targets, Meals, Supplements, Client-facing copy. Open on an “attention required” digest; mark engine checks as passed with drill-down evidence; persist reviewed sections; keep tabs for detail. Add approval error handling, retry, and a final confirmation summarizing exactly what will become client-visible.
+
+### [P-COACH|M3|src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:523] First-run guidance contains a dead-end route
+
+**Evidence:** Zero-client accounts receive a prominent welcome card and “+ Aggiungi il primo cliente,” but its `href` is `/clients/new` (`src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:523`; `src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:541`). The shipped route inventory lists `/plans/new` for intake (`docs/polish/baseline-sweep/manifest.json:119`) and the sidebar also points “Nuovo Cliente” there (`src/app/(dashboard)/sidebar.tsx:22`).
+
+**Deduction:** The single most important first-run action is internally inconsistent and likely lands on not-found. This is not polish debt; it breaks onboarding confidence before the coach reaches the product’s value.
+
+**Fix:** Point the CTA to `/plans/new` immediately. Then centralize route constants and add an e2e assertion that every empty-state CTA resolves. Replace the one-off welcome card with a persisted onboarding checklist whose next action is derived from actual client/snapshot/plan state.
+
+### [P-CLIENT|M3|src/app/portal/(protected)/dashboard/page.tsx:316] Portal query errors can masquerade as empty or partial content
+
+**Evidence:** The dashboard launches six queries and passes only `.data` and `.isLoading` into most child views; none of their `.error`/`.isError` values are rendered (`src/app/portal/(protected)/dashboard/page.tsx:316`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/dashboard/page.tsx:366`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/dashboard/page.tsx:373`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/dashboard/page.tsx:385`). The plan page likewise gives `ActivePlanView` only data and loading (`src/app/portal/(protected)/plan/page.tsx:13`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/plan/page.tsx:23`), so an errored query with undefined data reaches the “Nessun piano attivo” branch (`src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:106`). The diary query has no fetch-error branch (`src/app/portal/(protected)/diary/page.tsx:41`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/diary/page.tsx:94`), and Progress passes no errors for snapshots, profile, or documents (`src/app/portal/(protected)/progress/page.tsx:22`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/progress/page.tsx:47`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/progress/page.tsx:62`).
+
+**Deduction:** A client can be told there is no plan, no diary data, no measurement, or no document when the real condition is network/server failure. The route-level error boundary does not solve handled React Query errors, because these pages continue rendering. This is the encoded form of “silent death.”
+
+**Fix:** Standardize an async-view contract `{data, loading, error, refetch}` and prohibit undefined-as-empty. Render section-level retry states when one query fails, plus a page-level degraded-data notice when several fail. Log error codes without exposing internals. Only render empty states after a successful response explicitly returns empty.
+
+### [P-COACH/P-CLIENT|M3|src/app/(dashboard)/plans/page.tsx:113] State coverage is broad on lists but shallow and inconsistent
+
+**Evidence:** Coach list pages explicitly cover loading/error/empty: plans (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/page.tsx:113`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/page.tsx:126`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/page.tsx:142`), clients (`src/app/(dashboard)/clients/page.tsx:222`; `src/app/(dashboard)/clients/page.tsx:229`; `src/app/(dashboard)/clients/page.tsx:245`), invoices (`src/app/(dashboard)/invoices/page.tsx:283`; `src/app/(dashboard)/invoices/page.tsx:300`; `src/app/(dashboard)/invoices/page.tsx:306`), monitoring (`src/app/(dashboard)/monitoring/page.tsx:286`), and dashboard subqueries (`src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:597`; `src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:618`; `src/app/(dashboard)/dashboard/page.tsx:622`). Generate covers client loading/empty and mutation error but not client/estimate/preview query errors or success before redirect (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:243`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:575`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:596`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:1031`). Review covers page loading/error and save/share success/errors, but not approval failure (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:417`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:433`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:221`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:233`). Portal check-in and firma are the completeness benchmarks: each has loading, denial/error, pending, terminal and success branches (`src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:229`; `src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:248`; `src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:253`; `src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:206`; `src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:218`; `src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:234`; `src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:397`).
+
+**Deduction:** Coverage depends on the author and page, not a product-wide state model. Many loading states are centered text rather than shape-preserving skeletons, many errors require a full-page reload, and success feedback ranges from redirect-only to inline text to toast. Users must relearn what waiting, failure, and completion look like on each surface.
+
+**Fix:** Define shared `AsyncSection`, `EmptyState`, `ErrorState`, and mutation-feedback patterns with skeleton, retry, `aria-live`, and stable layout. Use them first on the required pages above. Add state-story tests for loading/empty/error/success and a checklist that forbids queries whose errors are ignored.
+
+### [P-COACH/P-CLIENT/P-PARTNER|M1/M8|src/app/globals.css:34] There are three competing brand systems
+
+**Evidence:** Global CSS defines a teal semantic brand ramp and explicitly describes patient warmth versus coach restraint (`src/app/globals.css:34`; `src/app/globals.css:39`; `src/app/globals.css:93`). The production code still contains 1,890 hex literals (141 unique), 186 raw zinc utilities, and only 32 `bg-brand*` uses; the sidebar uses zinc/near-black (`src/app/(dashboard)/sidebar.tsx:47`; `src/app/(dashboard)/sidebar.tsx:69`), while many portal cards use `#1a1a2e` and slate inline (`src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:123`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:142`). Plan PDFs define a separate navy/gold identity (`src/pdf/styles.ts:2`; `src/pdf/styles.ts:9`), and invoice/email templates revert to navy/gray (`src/pdf/invoice-renderer.ts:175`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:97`). Dark variables exist, but the file explicitly makes them inert and says the app is light-only (`src/app/globals.css:3`; `src/app/globals.css:50`). The font is system UI throughout (`src/app/globals.css:115`).
+
+**Deduction:** Roberto’s name is present, but the visual authorship is not. Teal, navy, zinc, blue gradients, and gold each claim to be the brand depending on the surface; typography supplies no distinctive voice. The palette behaves as local styling, not a cross-channel identity.
+
+**Fix:** Choose one cross-channel identity system with semantic roles, not page-specific palettes. Tokenize color, type scale, space, radius, elevation, and data-viz colors; expose print/email equivalents from the same source; migrate the core journeys before secondary admin pages. Add lint/CI rules against new raw color literals except approved data-viz/print contexts. Dark mode is optional; token discipline is not.
+
+### [P-COACH|M2/M3|src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:710] Intake has progress, but not continuity or transactional safety
+
+**Evidence:** The intake honestly declares seven named pages and shows current/total progress (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:710`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:715`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:731`). Only page one gates “Avanti”; later pages always proceed (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:830`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:838`). Submission first creates the client, then separately creates a snapshot, and only redirects on complete success (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:848`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:858`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:921`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/new/IntakeForm.tsx:949`). The manifest records that automated journey capture stopped at step two (`docs/polish/baseline-sweep/manifest.json:399`).
+
+**Deduction:** The progress bar gives orientation, but there is no visible draft persistence, “skip for now” meaning, completeness summary, or recovery if the second mutation fails after client creation. The coach can spend several minutes entering sensitive intake data and still face ambiguous partial completion.
+
+**Fix:** Persist a server-side draft per page, label required versus optional sections, provide save-and-exit/resume, and end with a completeness review. Make client+baseline creation transactional/idempotent or detect and resume a partially created client. Instrument where users stop rather than treating validation as a dead gate.
+
+### [P-CLIENT|M2/M6|src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:230] The plan is readable, but not designed around “what do I eat now?”
+
+**Evidence:** The plan view renders every populated day type, then every meal slot, its macros, meal name, and full ingredient/gram rows (`src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:233`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:239`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:259`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:264`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:275`). Ingredient quantities are protected from wrapping (`src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:278`), and supplements use an auto-fill grid with 180px minimum columns (`src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:299`; `src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:304`). There is no current-day/current-meal selection or progressive disclosure.
+
+**Deduction:** The actual deliverable is technically present but requires scrolling and translating a plan taxonomy into today’s action. Repeated macro labels compete with food and grams, while long ingredient names plus non-wrapping quantities can squeeze a 390px row. The experience optimizes completeness over use at the moment of eating.
+
+**Fix:** Lead with “Oggi” and current/next meal, with a seven-day switcher. Make food + quantity the primary row; collapse per-meal macros and alternate day types. Allow a focused meal view, substitutions, prep notes, and an explicit offline/PDF fallback. Test long Italian food names at 390px.
+
+### [P-CLIENT|M6|src/components/portal/portal-bottom-nav.tsx:36] Mobile structure is sound, but touch sizing is not enforced
+
+**Evidence:** The portal has a dedicated fixed bottom nav below `lg`, safe-area padding, and content clearance (`src/components/portal/portal-bottom-nav.tsx:36`; `src/components/portal/portal-bottom-nav.tsx:41`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/layout.tsx:46`). The shared portal container is fluid from mobile through desktop (`src/app/globals.css:156`). However, check-in’s 1–10 choices are 36×36px (`src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:101`; `src/app/portal/checkin/[token]/page.tsx:108`), the notification bell is 40×40px (`src/components/portal/notification-bell.tsx:14`; `src/components/portal/notification-bell.tsx:22`), and several controls use padding without a minimum 44px block size (`src/app/portal/(protected)/diary/page.tsx:89`; `src/components/portal/progress-photos-gallery.tsx:330`). Fixed/minimum widths are mostly wrapped or flexibly contained, which lowers 390px overflow risk (`src/components/portal/active-plan-view.tsx:151`; `src/components/portal/progress-photos-gallery.tsx:281`).
+
+**Deduction:** The responsive frame is better than the individual interactions. Frequent check-in targets and icon actions fall below a comfortable mobile target, and the absence of a shared target-size rule allows regressions. The 1–10 row also creates a dense horizontal decision on a narrow screen.
+
+**Fix:** Enforce `min-h-11 min-w-11` (prefer 48px for primary/frequent controls) in primitives and audit every portal action. Replace the ten-button scale with a large segmented/slider control that exposes the selected value and endpoints without tiny targets. Add 390px tests for overflow, keyboard appearance, safe-area, and zoomed text.
+
+### [P-COACH/P-CLIENT|M9|src/app/globals.css:131] Accessibility has good foundations but weak adoption
+
+**Evidence:** Global CSS forces a visible `:focus-visible` ring even over legacy inline `outline:none`, and disables animation/transition under reduced motion (`src/app/globals.css:131`; `src/app/globals.css:139`; `src/app/globals.css:143`). Production code contains 47 `aria-*` attributes; all four production `<img>` tags have alt attributes, including meaningful pose/date text for progress photos (`src/components/portal/progress-photos-gallery.tsx:446`; `src/components/portal/progress-photos-gallery.tsx:448`). Strong examples include chart `role="img"`/label (`src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:268`), sign-result focus transfer (`src/components/portal/sign-screen.tsx:201`), and weight input error association (`src/components/portal/log-weight-card.tsx:71`; `src/components/portal/log-weight-card.tsx:84`). But production also has 80 raw `<label>` tags and only 16 contain `htmlFor`; generator labels are siblings without control IDs (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:574`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:646`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:667`), as are diary fields (`src/app/portal/(protected)/diary/page.tsx:101`; `src/app/portal/(protected)/diary/page.tsx:111`). Low-emphasis text uses `#9ca3af` on the light portal background (`src/app/portal/(protected)/dashboard/page.tsx:341`) and `#a1a1aa` at 10–12px in review/generation (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:812`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:1051`).
+
+**Deduction:** Keyboard focus and reduced motion are strong global safeguards, but form semantics and contrast depend on local diligence. Visible labels that do not programmatically name their inputs increase screen-reader and voice-control friction. Small gray text is likely to be the first contrast failure when real displays, age, or glare enter the picture.
+
+**Fix:** Move all forms to shared `Label`/input primitives with generated IDs, descriptions and error links; add `aria-live` to async updates such as week preview. Run automated contrast and axe checks plus keyboard-only scripts on intake, generate, diary, check-in, and firma. Replace low-contrast microtext with semantic muted colors that are AA-verified at the actual size/weight.
+
+### [P-CLIENT|M7|src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:3] Charts show shape, not clinical meaning
+
+**Evidence:** `TrendChart` is responsive, handles zero/one/many points, supports pointer/touch tooltips, shows exact units, and offers metric/time-range controls (`src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:3`; `src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:152`; `src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:161`; `src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:241`; `src/components/charts/ChartControls.tsx:80`). It deliberately auto-scales every series to its own min/max so unlike units are “shape-comparable” (`src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:12`; `src/components/charts/TrendChart.tsx:195`). It has no y-axis, target band, goal line, change annotation, or textual trend interpretation; progress currently renders separate single-series charts only when two points exist (`src/components/portal/measurements-view.tsx:97`; `src/components/portal/measurements-view.tsx:103`).
+
+**Deduction:** The component is technically competent but can visually exaggerate tiny changes, and overlaid independently scaled series can imply correlation or equal magnitude that is not real. A client sees movement without knowing whether it is meaningful, expected, healthy, or connected to the plan.
+
+**Fix:** Use honest fixed/domain-aware scales or clearly separated small multiples; add axis/tick context, baseline, target/range bands, meaningful-change thresholds, and coach-authored annotations. Pair every chart with a sentence that says what changed and what to do, without awarding manipulative streaks for clinical outcomes.
+
+### [P-COACH/P-CLIENT|M10|src/lib/trpc/provider.tsx:20] Caching is configured, but mutations mostly refetch rather than feel instant
+
+**Evidence:** The shared React Query client uses a 30-second `staleTime` and one retry (`src/lib/trpc/provider.tsx:20`; `src/lib/trpc/provider.tsx:23`). Static/reference queries use 60 seconds or Infinity in targeted places (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:248`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/generate/page.tsx:356`; `src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:201`). No production `onMutate`, `setQueryData`, `cancelQueries`, suspense query, or placeholder/keep-previous-data flow is present in the audited source. Successful mutations generally invalidate/refetch; weight logging invalidates two query families (`src/components/portal/log-weight-card.tsx:34`; `src/components/portal/log-weight-card.tsx:39`), diary explicitly calls `refetch()` (`src/app/portal/(protected)/diary/page.tsx:43`), and one review operation schedules a full `window.location.reload()` (`src/app/(dashboard)/plans/[id]/review/page.tsx:1202`).
+
+**Deduction:** Network caching prevents some repeat waits, but actions do not usually update the visible model immediately. The product feels request/response-driven: click, disable, wait, refetch. Full reloads and non-debounced live previews amplify the sense that the UI is a thin shell over server operations.
+
+**Fix:** Add safe optimistic updates for reversible actions (mark read/reviewed, diary add, local plan edits), with rollback and toast receipts; use mutation results to update caches directly where possible. Keep server-confirmed treatment for irreversible/clinical actions. Add placeholder data to paginated/filter views, debounce preview inputs, and reserve full reload for genuinely unrecoverable state.
+
+### [P-CLIENT/P-PARTNER|M8/M1|src/pdf/styles.ts:1] Artifacts are more structured than the app, but not one family
+
+**Evidence:** The plan PDF has an A4 cover, RS mark, Roberto’s name, navy/gold palette, section headers, macro cards, day-type coding, tables, and footer (`src/pdf/styles.ts:41`; `src/pdf/styles.ts:74`; `src/pdf/html-renderer.ts:77`; `src/pdf/html-renderer.ts:485`). Invoice PDF has a clear brand/invoice header, party blocks, metadata, line items, totals and footer (`src/pdf/invoice-renderer.ts:7`; `src/pdf/invoice-renderer.ts:175`; `src/pdf/invoice-renderer.ts:230`; `src/pdf/invoice-renderer.ts:301`; `src/pdf/invoice-renderer.ts:362`). The engagement letter distinguishes draft, signed, unresolved placeholders and an eIDAS acceptance attestation (`src/pdf/engagement-letter-renderer.ts:121`; `src/pdf/engagement-letter-renderer.ts:127`; `src/pdf/engagement-letter-renderer.ts:178`; `src/pdf/engagement-letter-renderer.ts:189`). Yet plan PDF’s navy/gold differs from invoice/letter navy/gray and app teal. The plan cover is a typographic “RS” circle rather than a real identity asset (`src/pdf/styles.ts:85`; `src/pdf/html-renderer.ts:80`).
+
+**Deduction:** Artifact structure is one of the product’s strongest encoded surfaces, but the artifacts feel separately designed. Because the plan is the product’s deliverable and the invoice/signature establish trust, identity drift here is more costly than on a minor settings page.
+
+**Fix:** Create one artifact design kit sourced from shared brand data: logo/mark, credentials, contact block, typography, semantic colors, table rules, footer/legal pattern and version metadata. Keep artifact-specific hierarchy, but make plan, invoice, engagement letter, portal and emails unmistakably the same practice. Add rendered visual-regression fixtures for populated, long-content, and multi-page cases.
+
+### [P-CLIENT|M8/M5/M9|src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:87] Emails are consistent templates, but clinically generic and sometimes low-contrast
+
+**Evidence:** Automated emails share a 560px table wrapper with Roberto’s name, body and footer (`src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:87`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:101`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:114`). Plan-ready, check-in, invoice, feedback and measurement reminders use Italian headings, short explanation and one CTA (`src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:238`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:338`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:453`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:793`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:1029`). The plan-sharing router duplicates its own wrapper instead of using one template (`src/server/routers/plan.ts:53`), and the portal invite duplicates another full HTML document (`src/server/routers/client.ts:945`). Header copy uses `#6b7280` on `#1a1a2e`, and footer text uses `#d1d5db` on white (`src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:104`; `src/lib/inngest/functions.ts:117`), both risky contrast combinations at 11–13px.
+
+**Deduction:** The emails are functional and consistently Italian, but they sound like system notifications, not a continuing professional relationship. Duplication invites drift, while weak header/footer contrast can make Roberto’s identity and trust details recede.
+
+**Fix:** Consolidate all email rendering into typed templates with shared tokens and accessible tested contrast. Give each message a clear why/when/next step, Roberto sign-off and reply/support path; personalize with the relevant plan/check-in fact without exposing sensitive detail. Test Outlook/Gmail/mobile rendering and plain-text alternatives.
+
